To add HTTPS support in your local Nginx config​uration, you need to generate SSL certificates and configure the server block to listen on port 443. Here's a general guide:

1. Generate SSL Certificates:
   You can use tools like OpenSSL to generate self-signed certificates for local development. Run the following commands in your terminal:

   ```
   openssl req -x509 -nodes -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout localhost.key -out localhost.crt -days 365
   ```

2. Move the generated `localhost.crt` and `localhost.key` files to a secure location. Make sure to update the file paths in your Nginx config.

3. Edit your Nginx config file (commonly found at `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` or `/etc/nginx/sites-available/default`):

   ```nginx
   server {
       listen 443 ssl;
       server_name localhost;

       ssl_certificate /path/to/localhost.crt;
       ssl_certificate_key /path/to/localhost.key;

       location / {
           # Your existing configuration
       }
   }
   ```

4. Restart Nginx to apply the changes:

   ```
   sudo service nginx restart
   ```

After following these steps, your local Nginx server should now be configured to support HTTPS on port 443. Make sure to access your site using `https://localhost` in your browser.

