Sure! Here is an example of a basic to-do list code in React Native using functional components:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { View, Text, TextInput, Button, FlatList, StyleSheet } from 'react-native';

const TodoList = () => {
    const [todoItems, setTodoItems] = useState([]);
    const [newTodo, setNewTodo] = useState('');

    const addTodo = () => {
        if (newTodo.trim() !== '') {
            setTodoItems([...todoItems, newTodo]);
            setNewTodo('');
        }
    };

    return (
        <View style={styles.container}>
            <Text style={styles.title}>To-Do List</Text>
            <TextInput
                style={styles.input}
                value={newTodo}
                onChangeText={text => setNewTodo(text)}
                placeholder="Add a new to-do item"
            />
            <Button title="Add" onPress={addTodo} />
            <FlatList
                data={todoItems}
                renderItem={({ item }) => <Text>{item}</Text>}
                keyExtractor={(item, index) => index.toString()}
            />
        </View>
    );
};

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
    container: {
        flex: 1,
        padding: 20,
    },
    title: {
        fontSize: 24,
        fontWeight: 'bold',
        marginBottom: 10,
    },
    input: {
        borderWidth: 1,
        borderColor: '#ccc',
        padding: 10,
        marginBottom: 10,
    },
});

export default TodoList;
```

This code defines a simple to-do list component that allows users to add new to-do items.

To make a method in Java only callable by specific classes, you can use the `private` or `package-private` access modifier combined with defining those classes in the same package. Here's an example:

```java
public class MyClass {
    private void restrictedMethod() {
        System.out.println("This method can only be called by classes in the same package.");
    }
}

class AnotherClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyClass obj = new MyClass();
        // obj.restrictedMethod(); // This line would cause a compilation error as the method is private
    }
}
```

In this example, the `restrictedMethod` is `private` and can only be accessed within the `MyClass` itself. If you want it to be accessible to other classes within the same package, you can use the default access modifier (also known as package-private), which means not specifying any access modifier.

You can achieve this by creating a custom script in Google Sheets. Here is a basic example script that would copy a range of cells from one sheet to the last blank row of another sheet when a button is clicked:

```javascript
function copyToAnotherSheet() {
  var ss = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet();
  var sourceSheet = ss.getSheetByName('SourceSheetName');
  var targetSheet = ss.getSheetByName('TargetSheetName');

  var lastRow = targetSheet.getLastRow();
  var sourceRange = sourceSheet.getRange('A1:C1'); // Change this to whatever range you want to copy

  var targetRange = targetSheet.getRange(lastRow + 1, 1);
  sourceRange.copyTo(targetRange);
}
```

You can then insert a drawing (button) in your Google Sheets document, assign this script to it, and it will copy the specified range from 'SourceSheetName' to the next blank row in 'TargetSheetName'.
